Comment: What happens if someone just holds down all 4 buttons continuously?

Name: Robocraze
Comment: In that case, it would indeed consider it as a button press and you could beat the game. In order to fix this, you can use button states and only on a rising edge, set the button_pressed variable. So you can use last state and current state and check if last state is LOW and current state is HIGH, only then consider a button press.

Name: pdxfunk
Comment: Thanks for this! Question: What is the *t all about  in the callback? This is a deference of pointer t right? But I don't see where "t" shows up anywhere else.

Name: Shiv Capoor
Comment:
Hi,

The *t that you see in the callback function is a pointer to the timer object that is responsible for calling the callback function. As you have rightly observed, the * operator is the dereference operator, however in the context of a function parameter, this indicates a pointer to the timer corresponding to the call to the callback function. This provides you access to the timer object inside the callback function in case you need it. One example i can think of would be to maybe disable the timer or to change its parameters etc. it is not used inside the callback function since the operation being performed does not require any modifications to the original timer object. Hope this answers your question.

Comment:

You can use the function pwm_gpio_to_channel to get the channel connected to the gpio. The signature of this function is:

To read more about the function, please check the SDK documentation section 4.1.18.3.13. Link to the SDK documentation is given below:
https://datasheets.raspberrypi.org/pico/raspberry-pi-pico-c-sdk.pdf

Name: billkill37
Comment: If you play as a CB or a DMF, being strong is more important than being quick. As a CB, you should prioritize strengthening your upper body more (assuming that you already have a strong lower body, since you're a footballer), while maintaining/increasing your explosiveness and stamina. Don't be afraid to put on some weight, even if it's not all muscle, and lose a little bit of your explosiveness. You can make it up by being more strategic vs quick opponents. A physically stronger player is a lot more dangerous than a quick player inside the box. I started growing taller and larger around 16 years old and up until then, opposing attackers, who were stronger, were literally toying with my small ass. The coach benched me for almost a year before moving me to a DMF position. Now I am 1.82m, 78kg and I play mostly as a CB or a more defensive oriented DMF.

Name: LionTheBot 526
Comment: If you want to â€œupgradeâ€ your stamina in 3 days then here is what you need to do. Whenever you are benched make sure your being active. This way when coach subs you wont get tired running around. I have learned this the hard way and because of my mistake, i got my team a tie instead of a win (im a defender and i wasnâ€™t focusing because i was tired) Best ways to upgrade however is to do cardiovascular endurance/fitness exercises. This can include: Walking, Jogging, Running, Jumping Jacks, Cycling, Swimming, Aerobics, Rowing, Stair Climbing, Hiking, and so much more! Anything that gets your heart beating by doing a physical activity is considered a cardio exercise. In 3 days brother i shouldnâ€™t be saying this considering the fact that this was 3 years ago but this is for everyone; Stamina is cardiovascular endurance. You would also want to make sure you are CONSTANTLY working on one of these exercises to make sure you get the best out of your work. And brother 3 days is just way too short this isnâ€™t something that can happen overnight! What i suggest everybody to do is to really put that effort onto stuff like these. Stuff like this is not only good for your heart but it is good for your entire body as well!

Name: Tifle77 Tifle77
Comment:
What is a fartlek run?
Fartlek is literally, playing around with speeds â€“ essentially, itâ€™s a form of unstructured speedwork. It involves a continuous run in which periods of faster running are mixed with periods of easy- or moderate-paced running (not complete rest, as with interval training).

Fartlek (Swedish for â€˜speed playâ€™) is one of the most common training sessions I use with my athletes. The history of fartlek training dates back over 80 years, when coaches and scientists began to experiment with different methods of improving fitness and adding variety to training.

Name: KryptiK Knowledge
Comment:
Or... You can skip. Practice popping hard when skipping. Use all your legs range from ancle to knee and try going higher with each skip. 
Then try skipping up a hill. 
After a few sets of this do a sprint and see how your sprint feels. 
Focus on your steps and stride. 

After a while of doing these exercises you'll see a massive improvement in your sprint times and an overall improvement to the way you run. 
You can add weights too if you're more advanced and have been doing it enough.

Name: Violinistic
Comment:
Nope. This does not develop your speed. There is/should not no sprint portion here either. Sprint means running at top speed. If you run this lenght at top speed, no man on this earth will be able to do that again after 40 seconds. You would need 5 min rest minimum to do that. 20/40 is btw a typical aerobic session done at 70-80% of top speed at given distance as an aerobic workout. The aim is to develop a stronger heart.(Which means pumping blood more efficiently around with oxygenated blood cells which in praticwe means better stamina) This is what you do preparing for next season to build a foundation.
You want to build speed? You need 3-5 sec at top speed. So 50-60m at 100% with 4-5min rest period.
Something like 2x(4x60m) 5min rest, 10 between the 2 series. That.. will build your speed.

Name: dogboy0912
Comment:
Here's some more sprint workouts.
5x100m flat out sprint with walk back as rest
5x200m in 30s with 2 minute rest
Pyramid 1x100, 1x200, 1x300, 1x400, 1x300, 1x200, 1x100. Walk equal distance to your last distance ran or 2 minute rest, whichever is faster.

The goal with all of these is consistency. You want your last to be as fast as your first or even faster. The second to last can be slightly slower so you can go all out on your last. Think 80% of race pace.

Name: dogboy0912

Name: Max
Comment: 100m under 20 seconds? What it that? Primary school times? Also this exercise is 101 physical prep... You want a true exercise you do the "full works". Sprint half field, run backwards back to starting line, sprint the entire field, backward half field, side steps or knee pop on the entire width, sprint again half field forward. Shoot a free kick (for outside the box) or penalty or both, then either jog back to the start or repeat but going the other wait and do a volley shoot instead of FK. This alone will work your endurance, speed and end of run shoot in the worst possible conditions...

Name: Mind Control
Comment:
I was taught by a professional soccer player how to sprint. We do not properly sprint. This man firstly has too big of an upper body which slows him down with all that weight.

When ppl run they are jumping forward to their next step but if you have too much time in the air you are losing precious propulsion.

So in order to speed yourself up you must step shorter steps to to make it less of hopping and more of a pushing yourself forward and then pulling yourself forward.

The best way to learn the above technique is to of course run miles under time. Say a mile in 4 minutes.

Then to leg train your leg muscles. And get yourself a lean body type.

Once you have all of that you will find yourself out speeding fast guys that do not know to use more steps to get somewhere faster. 

Of course if you want to run a marathon u do not want to use more steps. You want to create rhythm in your body to use the least amount of energy. To generate the least amount of heat and to let your bodies stretchy tendons and ligaments expand and retract.

But what I learned in my soccer days was to walk to conserve energy and then when my time came to move I would be Lightning in a way that would generate a lot of heat but would be physically overwhelming not due to the fatigue but for their inability through lack of body mechanics for my defender to defend even if they knew it was coming

Name: FatLz
Comment: @Oliver Kalaizis itâ€™s to designate failure because realistically someone who is fit and does that often enough could just keep going for quite a long time if they didnâ€™t have something that would stop them from going too slow. The reason thatâ€™s a problem is because at a point youâ€™re going to be just running and not sprinting and when it gets to that point where youâ€™re taking longer to make it across youâ€™re going to start to build less fast twitch muscle fibers which are the type of muscle fibers that give you explosive strength and power and while slow twitch muscle fibers are better for endurance and lots of repetitive actions it will make you take longer to build that speed since running speed is mostly dictated by running form and more importantly how much of your body weight youâ€™re putting into the ground. For example Usain Bolt was able to put 7x his bodyweight in terms of power into the ground to propel himself when he was running. Granted iâ€™m not sure if this exercise is some magic recipe to running faster but it does make sense to limit your running to only explosive running for those reasons. It makes sense that once you canâ€™t explode while running so hard anymore that you cease your exercises as that comes more in line with how regular weight lifting is used to build fast twitch muscle fibers.

Do diet for the weight and do not do a crash diet make it slow and steady ie. If you want to lose 15kg do it in a period of 6 months.

All this period do slow jogging, and make sure you stay under 65% of your max heart rate.
And in the last months that you will be close to your ideal weight and with better stamina do HIIT and explosion and speed training more and more.
I think it is the most realistic training I can suggest

Also during the end try to do double trainings in one day.
One very early in the morning and one in the evening it will make your game explode.
And be patient and protect yourself from injuries

Comment: Sitting here as a 22 year old that used to play soccer up until college, itâ€™s bittersweet seeing such great advice from an equally great channel. Had a pretty shit coach for many years and it seems dumb now that they never talked about things like this. Happy though to see this being out there for the people!

Name: Tech Samurai
Comment:
What coach ever taught anything in the US?  The #1 lesson anyone should learn in soccer is that it's all up to you.  Don't rely on the coach, don't rely on the club, don't rely on your teammates (they won't play you if you're much better than them).

It's all up to the player!  The US is the hardest place to learn soccer due to the non-existence of coaching.  As Bobo Vieri said "the MLS is kung-fu and long balls" and he wasn't 99% right - he was 1000% right.  He said "you need youth academies" implying that the academies we have here are not soccer academies.  Part of that also is the result of no refereeing - we pay a bazillion dollars to refs who may as well be absent.

We have so many academies and no one to coach.  Sometimes I wish I could take over an academy like the Philadelphia Union and turn into Nick Bollettieri.  3 years with me - Ajax would be buying all their players from that club.

Name: Adio Aurel
Comment:
It's all in the feelings and you get the feel by practicing a lot. Go to a wall and practice passes without looking at the ball from various angles, low and high, strong, weak, etc. or get an adjustable rebound net, that's even more effective. For ideas check out some wall practice drill videos.
Once you gain confidence, you can observe the match better and get the feeling for your surroundings, where to run and where to expect the others would go and keep communicating: talking+hand signs where you pass or where you go and at times fake them to confuse your opponent.

Name: Ezekiel Duran
Comment: Best strategy I found was I would only take one step with my right, plant with my left and bang it low corner. Like 30% of the time side net and so hard for the goalie to make a commitment in such a quick move, I'd convert at least 90% in practice. Also such a small movement can be muscle memory trained easily, and it had little chance to open the hips so much as to miss the target. Furthermore is a personal story if you're still interested. My senior year of high school we had 7 penalties over the course of the season not a single converted by 7 different players. In fact I believe only one was on target.  I was pissed I didn't get to take one at all. I was new to the team, and a lot of the players had it out for me as I was new to the team, and better than them all. Even as a defender. There was only one player that gave me respect and he was a freshman so good on the ball but small and slower than average, still the next best to me. The worst was our first was in a pre season tournament final match against my former team (JV team) lol as my new team was far inferior, and I wanted it so badly as my relationship with their coach was sour. We would have gone up 3-1, but ended up losing 3-2 because momentum went their way. It was the only one I asked to take all season as a defender and because I knew nobody who stepped up would give up the chance to score as they all wanted to personally score more than they wanted a score. The worst TEAM I ever played on. I am always pass first. I'd rather assist than score anyway. Much more rewarding, as a brilliant pass gives another the opportunity to celebrate as much as me. And aren't the best moments in life better when shared with another?

Comment: As usual, you guys did a terrific video.  The Panenka move is underrated.  Yes, there is some risk, but statistics support the risk.  Most goalies are going to expect to move left or right with a penalty shot.   Statistically, all things being equal, the shot down the middle is the best move.

Name: Ezekiel Duran
Comment: @fsdts I guess their technique isn't really able to be determined pre kick, however the tendency to shoot middle is usually predictable based on his approach to the game, is all I was trying to say. Hopefully I didn't confuse that. The selfishness of a player in build up play, and in particular around the box is usually the factor that correlates with a penalty taker who has the tendency to shoot center

Name: Ezekiel Duran
Comment: @fsdts If they are a little cocky and selfish in build up play they will have the tendency to shoot in the middle more than a team player. It's just psychology. A show boater prefers the the flashiest option possible regardless of circumstance. Whereas the team player emphasizes success for the group as opposed to garnering attention. So a player who wants to shoot from open play whenever he has the ball as opposed to take a more logical team oriented approach, is the player more likely to shoot center on a penalty. It's not a guarantee but it's typical in their character traits. Hopefully that helps. Good luck

Name: fsdts
Comment: @Ezekiel Duran just wondering... how is an opponent's preferred penalty technique visible in their usual play? Not being obnoxious or anything, just really wondering how you are reading them, as I would like to use them during my games.

Name: Ezekiel Duran
Comment: Um no. Usually a player willing to go middle likes to stare down the goalie. I played goalie a lage part of my playing days, so When you have a guy who likes to go down the middle it is usually readable in everything he does on the pitch prior to the kick. Only first few minutes against unfamiliar opponents is when you should try the middle. Otherwise, there at least like 10 and a half to 11 feet between the goalie and either post as most humans (especially soccer/futbol players) aren't wide bodied. He can't be on both sides so shooting to one side especially if accurate enough, will convert much more often. Its simple logistics

Name: Ezekiel Duran
Comment: Long ago on a football pitch not so far away,  my team was in the final U 16 in Colorado springs. Annually 2nd largest youth tournament in Colorado only behind a U 19 event. We were on 10th penalty (our 5th) with the chance to win it all. My teammate tried the paneka and to the right, but hit it slow, with a little too much arch and the goalie didn't fully commit. He went to his knee reacting in time to stand up and save it top corner. We were pissed at the player and unfortunately lost on our 8th. A defender with little ability in shootouts shot a great hard low corner but the goalie wss good enough to save it. He felt terrible for a long time afterwards and the other guy who thought he was going pro didn't seem to care at all. He still thought he was best on the team overall, even though most would put him like 5th best player. Just cause he could do some Ronaldo skills he thought he was good, but really he lacked the wherewithal to make simple and obvious plays and usually ruined a lot of build ups for us. But yeah thats the only time I remember a player doing a paneka at an event I was in. Thanks for reading if you read it all

Name: 2DarkHorizon
Comment:
However there are 3 styles to dribble around an opponent. 

1. A proactive dribbler are only the truly fastest players can dribble around a defender proactively can force mistakes using speed. Which means when the defender is ready and is jockeying and the dribbler must make the first move forward. Therefore the dribbler needs to force the defender in a bad position using his speed. Only a few true dribblers were good at this Ryan Giggs, Ronadlo 9, Arjen Robben, Adama Traore, etc.

2. A passive dribbler that only can past a defender if the defender makes the first move and lunges in or makes a mistake first. Mid fielders are generally good at this as they need to maintain ball possession. Mid fieldiers have the space behind and to both sides of them so it is favored to dribble this style. Such players are Inestia. A good example is  Antonio Cassano he was a quite slow player but managed to go around players.

3. Using fakes and tricks even though the position with the ball is inescapable or unpassable the dribbler manages to evade for example using fake passes and fake kicks. Players like this are Eden Hazard and Ronaldiho and Zidane.

A dribbler can be a combination of any of these 3. However to achieve number 1 you need speed. The skill set of a proactive dribbler vs a passive dribbler is quite different. Sometimes you see a winger bad at keeping possession.

I had a game once against a team who had Really Really good 1v1 defenders, so their entire strategy was to get isolated and bait the 1v1.

Now as a Full back, I often came across 1v1s and usually won them. Obviously not this time. Luckily, my coach is an Analysis/Adapt kind of guy. So he changed our normally high pressure attack gameplan to a slow pace defense gameplan. 

We ended up managing to get a fastbreak goal and won 1-0 

Most of the game was spent just playing short passes between the defense though

Name: Eric
Comment: If a defender can take the ball away from you, then 1) he is faster/better than you, or 2) you have let him get closer to the ball than you. If you keep the ball closer to your foot than the opponent, then wait for him to commit and simply move the ball away from his incoming foot/tackle. I know this sounds trivial, but if you practice it, your reflexes become faster and reacting and moving the ball to keep it becomes faster and more intuitive. You have to put yourself in the situation where you practice reacting faster so the defender doesn't get the ball. Do this long enough, and eventually you will gain the upper hand on almost all defenders - mostly because you can control how close the ball stays to your foot. The best dribblers are acutely away of how far the ball is from their foot and how fast they can get to it, and when running at a defender allow the ball to stray a little too far from them intentionally, to goad the defender into committing. They will even push the ball off their foot in a randomized way, a little to the left or to the right, to make it seem like they don't really have control of the ball, it lures defenders into committing
